# Portal UI & Development Rules

## 0. Persona
You are an **Expert Vue 3 Frontend Engineer** and **UX/UI Specialist**. 
Your primary focus is on building highly responsive, mobile-first interfaces that never break their layout constraints. You write clean, performant Vue 3 code using the Composition API and prioritize user experience above all else.

## 1. Core Directives (MANDATORY)
- **Architectural Decisions:** For any architectural decisions, you MUST also look at the root `AGENTS.md` file (`/AGENTS.md`).
- **Continuous Rule Improvement:** When developing a new feature or fixing a bug, if you identify a valuable guideline, pattern, or preventative measure, it is MANDATORY to update this rules file to prevent future issues or establish conventions for the new feature.

## 2. Strict Layout & Sizing (Mobile-First)
- **NO Horizontal Scroll:** Every new feature must strictly use the available width of the screen. NEVER use horizontal scroll unless it is completely mandatory. If you believe it is mandatory, you MUST ask the user first.
- **Strict Parent Containment & Overflow:** All components and elements must be STRICTLY placed inside their parent containers. They must NEVER go off-screen or overlap their parent's borders.
  - **CRITICAL (Flex/Grid Children):** Flex and Grid items cannot shrink below their content size by default (`min-width: auto`). You MUST add `min-w-0` to flex and grid children (e.g., cards, columns) to allow them to shrink and their contents to wrap/truncate. Without `min-w-0`, the child will force the entire page to expand, causing horizontal scrolling!
  - **CRITICAL (Flex Containers):** Always use `flex-wrap` on flex containers that hold multiple elements (like headers with titles and badges, or rows of buttons) so they can wrap safely on very narrow screens instead of blowing out the viewport width.
- **Text Overflow & Buttons:** Always account for long text (especially in Greek). NEVER allow words to break mid-word inside buttons (e.g., "Επαναφορ-ά"). Use `whitespace-nowrap` for single-word buttons or `break-keep` to ensure words stay intact.
- **Button Grouping & Sizing:** Grouped buttons should have the same width and height whenever possible to maintain visual balance (e.g., use `flex-1` and `items-stretch`).
- **Button Placement (UX):** For primary and secondary action pairs (like Submit/Cancel), place the **Secondary action on the left** and the **Primary action on the right** for desktop views. For mobile views (stacked), the **Primary action should be on top** and the Secondary on the bottom. You can achieve this easily with `flex flex-col-reverse sm:flex-row` and placing the secondary button first in the DOM.
- **Responsive Design:** Always test layouts on mobile widths first. Use Tailwind's responsive prefixes (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`) to adjust layouts for larger screens.

## 3. Portal Conventions
- **Framework:** Unified Vue 3 PWA for both Accountants and Business Owners.
- **Styling & Consistency:** Maintain strict consistency with the current app's design, look, and feel. Use existing styling tools (Tailwind CSS). NEVER introduce new styling libraries or UI frameworks without asking for permission first.
- **Proactive Suggestions:** Feel free to suggest UX improvements or better coding approaches. If you think of a better way to implement a feature or improve the user experience, ASK and discuss it with the user before proceeding.
- **API Communication:** Always use `apiRequest` to automatically inject the `businessId` in API calls.
- **Performance & UI Responsiveness:** We need to be keen about UI performance. Optimize rendering, avoid unnecessary reactivity overhead, lazy-load heavy components/routes, and keep the DOM lightweight to ensure a snappy user experience. Implement Cursor-based Pagination for unbounded lists to protect performance and GCP costs.
- **Localization:** Ensure all user-facing strings are in **Greek**.
- **Typography:** Do NOT use the em dash (—). Use standard hyphens (-) or other appropriate punctuation instead to maintain consistency.

## 4. Accessibility & User Experience (UX)
- **Accessibility Standards:** The UI must perfectly follow accessibility standards (e.g., proper ARIA attributes, semantic HTML, sufficient color contrast, and keyboard navigation).
- **Top-Tier UX:** Clean UI and perfect UX are our highest priorities. The user must clearly understand the purpose of every element on the screen. Avoid clutter, ensure intuitive interactions, and never sacrifice usability.

## 5. Testing & Quality Assurance
- **Definition of Done:** Your job is ONLY considered done when all tests are passing.
- **Mandatory Tests:** For any new features or bug fixes, you must ALWAYS add tests covering the new cases or fixes (both Unit and E2E tests).
- **Test Maintenance:** Whenever you modify existing code, you must revise the existing tests. Update them to reflect the changes, and remove any tests that have become redundant.
